---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Morphological Quenching - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Morphological Quenching</h1>
        
        <div class="disambiguation">
            Not to be confused with <WikiLink slug="pages/Mass_Quenching" text="Mass Quenching" /> or <WikiLink slug="pages/Environmental_Quenching" text="Environmental Quenching" />
        </div>

        <div class="infobox">
            <h3 class="infobox-title">Morphological Quenching</h3>
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type:</th>
                    <td>Quenching mechanism</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Proposed by:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Martig_2009" text="Martig et al. (2009)" /></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Key Observable:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Bulge_to_Total_Ratio" text="B/T ratio" /> > 0.5</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Timescale:</th>
                    <td>~1-2 Gyr</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Related:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Stellar_Bulge" text="Stellar Bulges" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Disk_Stability" text="Disk Stability" /></td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Morphological quenching</strong> is a proposed mechanism by which the growth of a <WikiLink slug="pages/Stellar_Bulge" text="stellar bulge" /> can suppress <WikiLink slug="pages/Star_Formation" text="star formation" /> in galaxies, contributing to the <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Bimodality" text="galaxy bimodality" />. The theory suggests that bulge-dominated galaxies have stabilized gas disks that are less efficient at forming stars, even when cold gas is present.</p>

        <h2 id="section-0">Physical Mechanism</h2>
        
        <p>The presence of a massive stellar bulge affects star formation through several pathways:</p>
        
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Disk Stabilization</strong>: The deep potential well of the bulge increases the <WikiLink slug="pages/Toomre_Q" text="Toomre Q parameter" />, preventing gravitational instabilities</li>
            <li><strong>Shear Suppression</strong>: Enhanced shear in the inner galaxy disrupts <WikiLink slug="pages/Giant_Molecular_Clouds" text="giant molecular clouds" /></li>
            <li><strong>Altered Gas Dynamics</strong>: Changed orbital structure prevents efficient gas inflow to star-forming regions</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="section-1">Observational Evidence</h2>

        <div class="evidence-for">
            <h4>Supporting Evidence</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Strong correlation between <WikiLink slug="pages/Bulge_to_Total_Ratio" text="B/T ratio" /> and <WikiLink slug="pages/Specific_SFR" text="specific star formation rate" /> (sSFR)</li>
                <li>Bulge-dominated galaxies often contain <WikiLink slug="pages/Molecular_Gas" text="molecular gas" /> but show low star formation efficiency</li>
                <li><WikiLink slug="pages/S0_Galaxies" text="S0 galaxies" /> frequently have substantial HI reservoirs despite being quiescent</li>
                <li>Simulations show bulge growth can quench galaxies without gas removal</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="evidence-against">
            <h4>Challenges to the Theory</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Some bulge-dominated galaxies show active star formation (e.g., <WikiLink slug="pages/Pseudobulges" text="pseudobulges" />)</li>
                <li>The correlation with mass suggests <WikiLink slug="pages/Mass_Quenching" text="mass quenching" /> may be primary</li>
                <li>Difficult to separate morphology from other correlated properties</li>
                <li>Environmental effects often coincide with morphological changes</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 id="section-2">Relation to Other Quenching Mechanisms</h2>

        <p>Morphological quenching rarely acts in isolation:</p>
        
        <ul>
            <li><strong>vs <WikiLink slug="pages/Mass_Quenching" text="Mass Quenching" /></strong>: Both correlate with stellar mass, making separation challenging</li>
            <li><strong>vs <WikiLink slug="pages/AGN_Feedback" text="AGN Feedback" /></strong>: Bulge growth often triggers AGN activity</li>
            <li><strong>vs <WikiLink slug="pages/Environmental_Quenching" text="Environmental Quenching" /></strong>: Dense environments promote both bulge growth and gas stripping</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-3">Bulge Formation Pathways</h2>

        <p>The effectiveness of morphological quenching depends on how the bulge formed:</p>
        
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Major_Mergers" text="Major mergers" /> - Rapid bulge growth and strong quenching</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Disk_Instabilities" text="Disk instabilities" /> - Gradual bulge growth with moderate quenching</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Minor_Mergers" text="Minor mergers" /> - Can build bulges while maintaining some star formation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-4">Key Studies</h2>

        <ol>
            <li><strong>Martig et al. (2009)</strong> - Original proposal using hydrodynamical simulations</li>
            <li><strong>Saintonge et al. (2012)</strong> - COLD GASS survey showing gas in quenched galaxies</li>
            <li><strong>Wake et al. (2012)</strong> - Statistical separation of mass and morphology effects</li>
            <li><strong>Bluck et al. (2014)</strong> - Central stellar mass density as key parameter</li>
            <li><strong>Zheng et al. (2026)</strong> - Bulge mass/compactness delays bar formation through disk stabilization<sup>[1]</sup></li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="section-5">Open Questions</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Is morphology a cause or consequence of quenching?</li>
            <li>What B/T threshold triggers effective quenching?</li>
            <li>How do <WikiLink slug="pages/Pseudobulges" text="pseudobulges" /> vs <WikiLink slug="pages/Classical_Bulges" text="classical bulges" /> differ in quenching efficiency?</li>
            <li>Can morphological quenching be reversed?</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-6">Implications for Galaxy Evolution</h2>

        <p>If morphological quenching is significant, it implies:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Galaxy structure fundamentally regulates star formation</li>
            <li>Quenching can occur without complete gas removal</li>
            <li>The <WikiLink slug="pages/Hubble_Sequence" text="Hubble sequence" /> may represent an evolutionary pathway</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-7">See Also</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Quenching" text="Galaxy Quenching" /> - Overview of all quenching mechanisms</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Bulge_Formation" text="Bulge Formation" /> - How bulges grow</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Star_Formation_Efficiency" text="Star Formation Efficiency" /> - Gas-to-stars conversion</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Disk_Galaxy_Evolution" text="Disk Galaxy Evolution" /> - Morphological transformation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-8">References</h2>
        <ol class="references">
            <li>Zheng et al. (2026) - "Comparison of Bar Formation Mechanisms. IIIA. The role of classical bulges in spontaneous bar formation" arXiv:2603.12121</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="page-tags">
            <strong>Tags:</strong>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Quenching_Mechanisms" text="Quenching Mechanisms" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Galaxy_Structure" text="Galaxy Structure" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Theories" text="Theories" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Controversial" text="Controversial" />
        </div>
  </main>
</Base>
